{"title_page": "Greater China", "text_new": "{{short description|Region with commercial and cultural ties to the Han Chinese}}\n{{Infobox Chinese\n|s=\u5927\u4e2d\u534e\n|t=\u5927\u4e2d\u83ef\n|p=D\u00e0 Zh\u014dnghu\u00e1\n|j=daai6 zung1 waa4<!--For Hong Kong and Macau-->\n|poj=T\u0101i Tiong-h\u00f4a\n|order=st}}\n<!--[[File:Greater China.GIF|300px|thumb|Approximate range map of Greater China, which includes Mainland China, Macau, Hong Kong and Taiwan]]-->\n\n\"'''Greater China'''\" is a controversial term which was firstly described by some Chinese scholars to encompasses [[mainland China]], [[Hong Kong]], [[Macau]] and may include other [[overseas Chinese]] communities throughout the world, notably [[Singapore]] because these places attract many Chinese emigrants.<ref name=\"Journal1\">{{Cite journal|title=The concept of greater China in higher education: adoptions, dynamics and implications|journal = Comparative Education|volume = 52|pages = 26\u201343|last=William|first=Yat Wai Lo|doi=10.1080/03050068.2015.1125613|year = 2016|quote=This term can be narrowly defined as referring to a geographic concept that consists of the People's Republic of China, the Republic of China, the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region and the Macau Special Administrative Region, where ethnic Chinese comprise the majority of the population. In this sense, the term is used to describe the ethnic and the associated political, economic and cultural ties among these Chinese societies (Harding 1993; Cheung 2013).}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Journal2\">{{Cite journal|last=William|first=Yat Wai Lo|year=2016|title=The concept of greater China in higher education: adoptions, dynamics and implications|journal=Comparative Education|volume=52|pages=26\u201343|doi=10.1080/03050068.2015.1125613|quote=However, some analysts see the Greater China concept as a way to summarise \u2018the linkages among the fair-flung international Chinese community\u2019, thereby incorporating Singapore and overseas Chinese communities in their usage of the term (Harding 1993, 660; also see Wang 1993).}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Harding|first=Harry|date=December 1993|title=The Concept of \u201cGreater China\u201d: Themes, Variations and Reservations*|url=https://www.cambridge.org/core/journals/china-quarterly/article/concept-of-greater-china-themes-variations-and-reservations/FAED34F84F7A8CF25CB3328991218293|journal=The China Quarterly|language=en|volume=136|pages=660\u2013686|doi=10.1017/S030574100003229X|issn=1468-2648|via=}}</ref>\n\nHowever, many Taiwanese don't believe themselves to be a part of greater China as it gives impression that Taiwan is part of China.<ref name=\"Taiwan Business TOPICS 2018\">{{cite web | title=Does Taiwan Belong In \u201cGreater China?\u201d | website=Taiwan Business TOPICS | date=2018-05-16 | url=https://topics.amcham.com.tw/2018/05/does-taiwan-belong-in-greater-china/ | access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref><ref name=\"JSTOR\">{{cite web | title=China and Taiwan: Not Yet 'Greater China' on JSTOR | website=JSTOR | url=https://www.jstor.org/stable/2620593?seq=1 | access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref><ref name=\"National Sun Yat-Sen University\">{{cite web | author=Jeanette Ka-yee Yuen | title=The Myth of Greater China? Hong Kong as a prototype of Taiwan for Unification | website=Taiwan in Comparative Perspective | date=2020-03-22 | url=http://archive.is/Jgq9F | access-date=2020-03-22 | issn=1752-7732 |  others=Taiwan Research Programme, London School of Economics}}</ref>\n\n==Usage==\n\n===Commercial usage===\n\n[[Multinational corporation|Multinational corporations]] frequently use the term to name their regional [[Corporate headquarters|headquarters]]. For example, [[Procter & Gamble|P&G]] uses it to name its regional headquarter in [[Guangzhou]] that also operates in Hong Kong and [[Taipei]].<ref>{{cite web |title=P&G in Greater China |url=https://www.pgcareers.com/location-greaterchina |website=www.pgcareers.com |accessdate=16 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> [[Apple Inc.|Apple]] uses it for its regional headquarter in Shanghai.<ref>{{cite news |title=Isabel Ge Mahe named Apple\u2019s managing director of Greater China |url=https://www.apple.com/newsroom/2017/07/isabel-ge-mahe-named-apple-managing-director-of-greater-china/ |accessdate=16 March 2020 |work=Apple Newsroom}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Mickle |first1=Andrew Dowell and Tripp |title=Apple Closes All Its Stores Outside China Over Coronavirus |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/apple-closes-all-its-stores-outside-china-over-coronavirus-11584172214 |website=Wall Street Journal |accessdate=16 March 2020 |date=14 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Academic usage===\n\n[[Universities]] among other [[research institutions]] such as [[Columbia University]] use the term for studies of the region.<ref>{{cite web |title=Greater China - Weatherhead East Asian Institute |url=http://weai.columbia.edu/research/regions/china-region/ |website=weai.columbia.edu |accessdate=16 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Political usage===\nThe term is often used to avoid invoking sensitivities over the [[political status of Taiwan]].<ref name=\"Aretz 2007\"/>\n\n==History==\n[[File:China Proper 1944.png|thumb|left|250px|The map of \"China\" in the 1944 American [[propaganda film]] ''[[The Battle of China]]'', distinguishing \"[[China proper]]\" from [[Manchuria]], \"Mongolia\" (here [[Pan-Mongolism|Greater Mongolia]] including [[Mongolia|the present country]], the [[Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region]], and [[Tuva]]), [[Xinjiang|Sinkiang]], and [[Tibet]].]]\nThe term has been used for a long time, but with differing scope and connotations.\n\nIn the 1930s [[George Cressey]] used it to refer to the entire [[Qing Dynasty|Chinese Empire]], as opposed to [[China proper]].<ref name=\"Harding\">{{cite journal\n  | first = Harry\n  | last = Harding\n  | title = The Concept of 'Greater China': Themes, Variations and Reservations\n  | journal = The China Quarterly\n  | issue =  136, Special Issue: Greater China\n  | pages = 660\n  | date = December 1993}}\n</ref> Usage by the United States on government maps in the 1940s as a political term included territories [[History of the Republic of China|claimed by the Republic of China]] that were part of the previous empire, or geographically to refer to topographical features associated with China that may or may not have lain entirely within Chinese political borders.<ref name=\"Harding\" /> \n\nThe concept began to appear again in Chinese-language sources in the late 1970s, referring the growing commercial ties between the mainland and Hong Kong, with the possibility of extending these to Taiwan, with perhaps the first such reference being in a Taiwanese journal ''Changqiao'' in 1979.<ref name=\"Harding\" />{{verification needed|date=March 2020}} \n\nThe English term subsequently re-emerged in the 1980s to refer to the growing economic ties between the regions as well as the possibility of political unification.<ref name=\"Harding\" /> It is not an institutionalized entity such as the [[European Union|EU]] or [[Association of Southeast Asian Nations|ASEAN]]. The concept is a generalization to group several markets seen to be closely linked economically and does not imply [[sovereignty]].<ref name=\"Aretz 2007\">{{cite book  | first = Tilman  | last = Aretz  | title = The greater China factbook  | publisher = Taiwan Elite Press  | location = Taipei  | year = 2007  | url = http://www.books.com.tw/exep/prod/booksfile.php?item=0010380377  | isbn = 978-986-7762-97-9 <!--9867762975-->  | oclc = 264977502  | url-status = live  | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20090131200221/http://www.books.com.tw/exep/prod/booksfile.php?item=0010380377  | archivedate = 2009-01-31  }}</ref>\n\n== Controversy ==\n\nFor some Asians{{who|date=March 2020}}, the term is a reminder of the \"[[Greater East Asia Co-Prosperity Sphere]]\", a euphemism for the region controlled by [[Empire of Japan|Imperial Japan]] during the [[Second World War]].<ref>{{cite journal\n  | last = Shambaugh\n  | first = David\n  | title = Introduction: The Emergence of 'Greater China'\n  | journal = The China Quarterly\n  | issue =  136, Special Issue: Greater China\n  | pages = 654\n  | date = December 1993}}\n</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|China|Hong Kong|Taiwan|Singapore}}\n\n{{colbegin}}\n* [[Adoption of Chinese literary culture]]\n* [[Bamboo network]]\n* [[East Asian cultural sphere]]\n* [[History of China]]\n* [[List of tributaries of China]]\n* [[Nine-dash line]]\n* [[Sinophone]]\n* [[Greater India]]\n{{colend}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Chinese nationalism]]\n[[Category:Country classifications|China, Greater]]\n[[Category:Cross-Strait relations]]\n[[Category:Cultural regions|China, Greater]]\n[[Category:Geography of China]]\n[[Category:Historical regions]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Region with commercial and cultural ties to the Han Chinese}}\n{{Infobox Chinese\n|s=\u5927\u4e2d\u534e\n|t=\u5927\u4e2d\u83ef\n|p=D\u00e0 Zh\u014dnghu\u00e1\n|j=daai6 zung1 waa4<!--For Hong Kong and Macau-->\n|poj=T\u0101i Tiong-h\u00f4a\n|order=st}}\n<!--[[File:Greater China.GIF|300px|thumb|Approximate range map of Greater China, which includes Mainland China, Macau, Hong Kong and Taiwan]]-->\n\n\"'''Greater China'''\" is a controversial term which was firstly described by some Chinese scholars to encompasses [[mainland China]], [[Hong Kong]], [[Macau]], [[Taiwan]] and may include other [[overseas Chinese]] communities throughout the world, notably [[Singapore]] because these places attract many Chinese emigrants.<ref name=\"Journal1\">{{Cite journal|title=The concept of greater China in higher education: adoptions, dynamics and implications|journal = Comparative Education|volume = 52|pages = 26\u201343|last=William|first=Yat Wai Lo|doi=10.1080/03050068.2015.1125613|year = 2016|quote=This term can be narrowly defined as referring to a geographic concept that consists of the People's Republic of China, the Republic o