nked economically and does not imply [[sovereignty]].<ref name=\"Aretz 2007\">{{cite book  | first = Tilman  | last = Aretz  | title = The greater China factbook  | publisher = Taiwan Elite Press  | location = Taipei  | year = 2007  | url = http://www.books.com.tw/exep/prod/booksfile.php?item=0010380377  | isbn = 978-986-7762-97-9 <!--9867762975-->  | oclc = 264977502  | url-status = live  | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20090131200221/http://www.books.com.tw/exep/prod/booksfile.php?item=0010380377  | archivedate = 2009-01-31  }}</ref>\n\n== Controversy ==\n\nFor some Asians{{who|date=March 2020}}, the term is a reminder of the \"[[Greater East Asia Co-Prosperity Sphere]]\", a euphemism for the region controlled by [[Empire of Japan|Imperial Japan]] during the [[Second World War]].<ref>{{cite journal\n  | last = Shambaugh\n  | first = David\n  | title = Introduction: The Emergence of 'Greater China'\n  | journal = The China Quarterly\n  | issue =  136, Special Issue: Greater China\n  | pages = 654\n  | date = December 1993}}\n</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|China|Hong Kong|Taiwan|Singapore}}\n\n{{colbegin}}\n* [[Adoption of Chinese literary culture]]\n* [[Bamboo network]]\n* [[East Asian cultural sphere]]\n* [[History of China]]\n* [[List of tributaries of China]]\n* [[Nine-dash line]]\n* [[Sinophone]]\n* [[Greater India]]\n{{colend}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Chinese nationalism]]\n[[Category:Country classifications|China, Greater]]\n[[Category:Cross-Strait relations]]\n[[Category:Cultural regions|China, Greater]]\n[[Category:Geography of China]]\n[[Category:Historical regions]]\n", "name_user": "165.225.112.194", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Greater_China"}
